<h3><a name="Name"></a>Name</h3>
<blockquote><b>plconfig</b> - the Pipeline Configuration Tool<br>
</blockquote>
<h3><a name="Synopsis"></a>Synopsis</h3>
<blockquote><b>plconfig</b> [<a href="#Global_Options"><span
 style="font-style: italic;">options</span></a>]<br>
  <br>
  <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span> <a
 href="--graphical"><span style="font-weight: bold;">--graphical</span></a><br>
  <i> </i><br>
  <b>plconfig</b> <a style="font-weight: bold;" href="#--help">--help</a><br>
  <b>plconfig</b> <a style="font-weight: bold;" href="#--html-help">--html-help</a><br>
  <b>plconfig</b> <a style="font-weight: bold;" href="#--version_">--version</a><br>
  <b>plconfig</b> <a style="font-weight: bold;" href="#--release-date">--release-date</a><br>
  <b>plconfig</b> <a style="font-weight: bold;" href="#--copyright">--copyright</a><br>
  <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span> <a href="#--license"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">--license</span></a><br>
</blockquote>
<h3><a name="Description"></a>Description<br>
</h3>
<blockquote>This program is used by system administrators to generate a
Pipeline configuration profile and license key for their site.&nbsp;
See the <a href="#Global_Options"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Global
Options</span></a> section for details about the site specific
parameters which can be configured.<br>
  <h4>Before You Start<br>
  </h4>
Before running this program, a new user called (pipeline) who's user
group is also called (pipeline) needs to be created at your site.&nbsp;
The <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1) program must
be
run as the (pipeline) user.&nbsp; This user will eventually be used
to run various daemon processes and other privileged programs which
make up the Pipeline system.&nbsp; The (pipeline) user should be able
to login to
all hosts which will run Pipeline programs with an identical user and
group ID.&nbsp; Once a site configuration profile has been generated
using <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1), the user
ID and group ID for this user should not be modified.<br>
  <br>
In addition, the root installation directory (see <a href="#--root-dir"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">--root-dir</span></a>) for Pipeline needs
to be
created and have its file access permissions and ownership set before
running <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1) exactly as
follows:<br>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
  <code>&gt; mkdir <span style="font-style: italic;">root-install-directory<span
 style="font-style: italic;"><br>
  </span></span>&gt; chown root.pipeline <span
 style="font-style: italic;">root-install-directory<br>
  </span>&gt; chmod 775<span style="font-style: italic;"> </span><span
 style="font-style: italic;"><span style="font-style: italic;">root-install-directory</span></span><span
 style="font-style: italic;"><span style="font-style: italic;"></span></span></code></div>
  <br>
Where the (<span style="font-style: italic;">root-install-directory</span>)
is replaced with the location chosen for the Pipeline installation for
your site.&nbsp; Once these steps have been taken, you are ready to
configure PIpeline for your site.<code><span style="font-style: italic;"></span></code><br>
  <h4>Configuring Pipeline</h4>
Once the steps described above, its a relatively simple matter to
generate the Pipeline configuration and license key.&nbsp; <br>
  <br>
If run in graphical mode, <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
only requires the <a href="--graphical"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">--graphical</span></a> option and will
display a set of dialogs which will walk you through the configuration
process.<br>
  <br>
Otherwise, <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1) is run
in command-line mode and requires a core set of options described in
the <a href="#Required_Options"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Required
Options</span></a> section.&nbsp; The rest of the options are not
required and the configuration parameters they control are either
auto-detected by <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
or given reasonable default values.&nbsp; The choices for all
configuration parameters will be printed by <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1) when run.&nbsp; <br>
  <br>
Regardless of whether <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
is run in graphical or command-line mode, it
writes (or overwrites) the following three files under the root
installation directory (see <a href="#-root-dir"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">--root-dir</span></a>):<br>
  <span style="font-style: italic;"><br>
  <a name="pipeline.key"></a>root-install-directory</span>/config/pipeline.key<br>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
This file contains the license key for Pipeline for your site.&nbsp;
This file should be zealously protected as it
represents confidential information covered by the <a
 href="#License_Agreement"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Pipeline
Configuration Tool License Agreement</span></a>.
Once
Pipeline is installed, this file will be required in order to run the
programs which make up the Pipeline.<br>
  </div>
  <br>
  <span style="font-style: italic;"><a name="pipeline.profile"></a>root-install-directory</span>/config/pipeline.profile<br>
  <br>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;">This file contains the site specific
configuration profile data which will be used build the custom Pipeline
distribution for your site.&nbsp; The contents of
this file will need to be pasted into the <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Site Profile</span> section of the online <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Pipeline License Application Form</span>. <br>
  <br>
  </div>
  <span style="font-style: italic;"><a name="pipeline.config"></a>root-install-directory</span>/config/pipeline.config<br>
  <br>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;">This is a plain text file similar to
the configuration parameters printed by<span style="font-weight: bold;">
plconfig</span>(1).&nbsp; This file is not required either to run
Pipeline or as part of the license application process.&nbsp; Its
provided solely for your future reference of the configuration settings
you chose when generating the other two files.<br>
  <br>
  </div>
Once you've decided on a configuration, you should run <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1) one last time adding the
  <a href="--lock"><span style="font-weight: bold;">--lock</span></a>
option the rest of your option choices. This option make the above
three file read-only to prevent any accidental destruction at a later
date by running <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
again.<br>
  <h4><span style="font-weight: bold;">Obtaining and Installing Pipeline</span></h4>
Once you have successfully completed the configuration process above, a
distribution of Pipeline configured for your site may be obtained by
completing the <span style="font-weight: bold;">Pipeline License
Application Form</span>.&nbsp; Pipeline is distributed as an <a
 href="http://rpm.org/"><span style="font-weight: bold;">RPM</span></a>
which is customized for your site.&nbsp; Once your license application
as been processed, you will be sent an email containing the download
location for this custom RPM specific to your site.&nbsp; <br>
  <h4><a name="System_Prerequisites"></a>System Prerequisites</h4>
Pipeline requires that the master server, file server and any hosts
which be part of the Pipeline job execution queue run the Linux (kernel
version 2.4 or later) operating system.&nbsp; Support for other flavors
of UNIX are possible as long as they support the same file system
related system calls as Linux.<br>
  <br>
In order to enable the full functionality of the Pipeline command-line
and graphical client programs, they must also be run on a Linux
host.&nbsp; However, these client programs are written entirely in Java
and may be run on any host which has a functional Java VM with some
loss of functionality.&nbsp; The biggest limitation is that
editor/viewer programs cannot be launched by non-Linux Pipeline
clients.&nbsp;
Otherwise, all other Pipeline operations are functional on non-Linux
machines.<br>
  <br>
Finally, both Pipeline client and server programs are heavily dependent
on Java.&nbsp; Even the <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
tool depends on at least the Java Runtime Environment.<br>
  <br>
The
existence and locations of the following Java
prerequisites are checked by <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
when run and can be customized by the <a href="#--class-path"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">--class-path</span></a> and <a
 href="#--library-path"><span style="font-weight: bold;">--library-path</span></a>
options:<br>
  <br>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><a href="http://java.sun.com/"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Java Runtime Environment</span></a><br>
  <span style="font-weight: bold;"></span></div>
  <div style="margin-left: 80px;">J2SE (1.5.0 or later)<br>
  </div>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
  <a href="http://java.sun.com/products/jce/"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Java Cryptography Extension</span></a><br>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;"> Unlimited Strength Jurisdiction
Policy Files</div>
  <br>
  <a href="http://java.sun.com/products/java-media/jai/"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;"></span></a><a
 href="http://java.sun.com/products/java-media/jai/"
 style="font-weight: bold;">Java Advanced Imaging<span
 style="font-weight: bold;"> </span></a><br>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;">JAI (1.1.2 or later)<br>
JAI Image I/O API (1.0 or later)<br>
  <br>
  </div>
  <span style="font-weight: bold;"></span><span
 style="font-weight: bold;"><a
 href="http://java.sun.com/products/java-media/3D/">Java 3D Library</a><br>
  </span>
  <div style="margin-left: 40px;">Java 3D API (1.3.1 or later)<br>
  </div>
  </div>
