<h3><a name="Global_Options"></a>Global Options</h3>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">
<h4>Graphical Mode Option<br>
</h4>
<span style="font-weight: bold;"><a name="--graphical"></a>--graphical</span><br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
Display a set of graphical dialogs which will walk you through the
configuration process. If this option is given, it must be the only
option to <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1).&nbsp;
If this option is not given, <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
will operate in non-graphical mode.<br>
</div>
</div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><a name="Required_Options"></a>Required
Options</h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px; font-weight: normal;">If run in
non-graphical mode, the following set of options must be specified each
time <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1) is run. These
options control the minimal set of configuration parameters required
for any site.<br>
</h4>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 40px;"><b><a
 name="--root-dir"></a>--root-dir</b>=<span style="font-style: italic;">dir</span></h4>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 80px;">The path
to the root installation directory (<span style="font-style: italic;">dir</span>)
of Pipeline.&nbsp; All
programs and data files which make up Pipeline will live under this
directory when Pipeline is installed.&nbsp; This directory should
reside on a network accessible file system such that all machines which
will run Pipeline related programs can access the directory as (dir). <br>
</h4>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 80px;">This directory must
exist and be writable by the "pipeline" user at the time <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1) is run.</h4>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><span style="font-weight: bold;"><a
 name="--evaluation"></a>--evaluation</span><br
 style="font-weight: bold;">
<span style="font-weight: bold;"><a name="--anual"></a>--annual</span><br
 style="font-weight: bold;">
<span style="font-weight: bold;"><a name="--perpetual"></a>--perpetual<br>
</span>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
Specifies the time period the Pipeline license will remain valid.&nbsp;
An evaluation license is valid for 30-days. An annual license is valid
for one year.&nbsp; A perpetual license is valid forever.&nbsp; One and
only one of these options must be given.<br>
</div>
</div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><a name="Non-Required_Options"></a>Non-Required
Options</h4>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">If run in non-graphical mode, the
following set of options are not required but may be used to customize
the configuration parameters for your site which would otherwise be
auto-detected or given default values.<br>
<br>
<span style="font-weight: bold;"><a name="--domain"></a>--domain</span>=<span
 style="font-style: italic;">name<br>
</span><span style="font-weight: bold;"><a name="--ip-mask"></a>--ip-addrs</span>=<span
 style="font-style: italic;">pattern</span>[,pattern]<br>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;">
One of these two options can be
used to configure the set of hosts which will be considered the site
for which Pipeline is licensed.&nbsp; These two options are mutually
exclusive.&nbsp; If neither option is given, then domain name based
licensing will be used and the name of the domain will be determined
from the the name of
the machine running <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1).<br>
<br>
If the <b>--domain</b> option is
given, the site will be considered to be all machines who's fully
qualified
name are members of the given domain (<span style="font-style: italic;">name</span>).&nbsp;
The machine running <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
must currently be a member of this domain and the domain must be
registered to the Pipeline license applicant.<br>
<br>
If the <b>--ip-addrs</b> option is
given, the site will be defined by combining the set of IP address
patterns given (<span style="font-style: italic;">pattern</span>).&nbsp;
An IP address pattern can either specifiy a single address using a
standard IP address such as (194.24.48.145) or a set of related
addresses where one of the last two address numbers are replaced by a
wildcard (*) or a range.&nbsp; For example, for following IP address
patterns are legal:&nbsp; (194.24.48.*), (194.24.48.[12-30,32,50-63]),
(194.24.[48,49].*).&nbsp; The machine running <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1) must have one of the IP
addresses specified by the patterns and all of the IP addresses must be
registered to the Pipeline license applicant.<br>
</div>
</div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><b><a name="--home-dir"></a>--home-dir</b><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">=</span><span
 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: normal;">dir</span></h4>
<div style="margin-left: 80px;">The absolute path to the parent
directory of all user home
directories.&nbsp; <br>
<br>
If not specified, this location is derived
from the environment under which <span style="font-weight: bold;">plconfig</span>(1)
is run or (/home) if the location cannot be determined from the
environment.<br>
<br>
</div>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><b><a name="--toolset-dir"></a>--toolset-dir</b>=<span
 style="font-style: italic;"><span style="font-style: italic;">dir</span></span><br>
<span style="font-style: italic;"><span style="font-style: italic;"></span></span></div>
<div style="margin-left: 80px;"><span style="font-style: italic;"><span
 style="font-style: italic;"><br>
</span></span>
The absolute path to the root directory
(<span style="font-style: italic;">dir</span>) of the installed
toolsets for the site.&nbsp; Toolsets represent named shell
environments under which various Pipeline editors and jobs are
run.&nbsp; A toolset is simply a shell script containing only
environmental variable definitions.&nbsp; The location chosen for
toolsets normally is on a network accessible file system.&nbsp;
Alternatively, this directory may be located on a local file system on
each machine which is kept consistent via some automated process such
as <span style="font-weight: bold;">rdist</span>(1). In either case,
this directory needs to be accessible from all machines which will run
Pipeline related programs and have a consistent contents.<br>
<br>
If not specified, the toolset directory will default to (/base/toolset).<br>
<span style="font-weight: bold;"><br>
</span></div>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><span style="font-weight: bold;"><a
 name="--temp-dir"></a>--temp-dir</span>=<span
 style="font-style: italic;">dir</span><br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
The absolute path to the directory (<span style="font-style: italic;">dir</span>)
used to write various temporary files generated by Pipeline
programs.&nbsp; For optimal performance, this directory should reside
on a local file system.<br>
<br>
If not specified, the temporary directory will default to (/usr/tmp).<br>
<br>
<br>
</div>
</div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><b><a name="--master-host"></a>--master-host</b><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">=</span><span
 style="font-style: italic; font-weight: normal;"><span
 style="font-style: italic;">host</span></span><br
 style="font-weight: normal;">
</h4>
<div style="margin-left: 80px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The
host name of the machine (<span style="font-style: italic;">host</span>)
which will run the Pipeline master server </span>plmaster<span
 style="font-weight: normal;">(1) daemon.&nbsp; This
daemon should run on a host which can access the root node directory
(see </span><a style="font-weight: bold;"
 href="file:///home/jim/code2/src/plconfig/docs/man/--node-dir">--node-dir</a><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">)
on a local file system.&nbsp; The master server daemon is responsible
for managing all Pipeline node operations including dispatching
jobs.&nbsp; For optimal performance, the host which runs this daemon
should be dedicated and have a fast network connection to the host
running the Pipeline file management </span>plfilemgr<span
 style="font-weight: normal;">(1)
daemon (see </span><a style="font-weight: bold;"
 href="file:///home/jim/code2/src/plconfig/docs/man/--file-host">--file-host</a><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">).&nbsp; <br>
<br>
</span><span style="font-weight: normal;">If not specified, the master
host will default to (localhost).<br>
</span></div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><b><a name="--master-port"></a>--master-port</b><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">=</span><i style="font-weight: normal;">num</i></h4>
<div style="margin-left: 80px;">The number of the network port (<span
 style="font-style: italic;">num</span>) listened to by the Pipeline
master server <span style="font-weight: bold;">plmaster</span>(1)
daemon.&nbsp; <br>
<br>
If not specified, the port number will default to (53135).<br>
</div>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 40px;"><b><a
 name="--node-dir"></a>--node-dir</b>=<span style="font-style: italic;">dir</span></h4>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 80px;">The absolute path
to the root directory under which the persistent copies of Pipeline
nodes and node related information are stored.&nbsp; This directory
should
reside on a local file system on the host which will run the Pipeline
master server <span style="font-weight: bold;">plmaster</span>(1)
daemon (see <a
 href="file:///home/jim/code2/src/plconfig/docs/man/--master-host"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">--master-host</span></a>).&nbsp; <br>
</h4>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 80px;">If not specified,
the node directory will default to (/usr/share/pipeline).</h4>
<br>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><b><a name="--file-host"></a>--file-host</b><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">=</span><span style="font-style: italic;"><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">host</span></span><br>
<span style="font-style: italic;"></span></div>
<div style="margin-left: 80px;">The host name of the machine (host)
which will run both the Pipeline file management <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plfilemgr</span>(1)
daemon and the<span style="font-weight: normal;"> directory change
notification daemon <span style="font-weight: bold;">plnotify</span>(1)</span>
.&nbsp; These two daemons should be run on the same host which acts as
the
network file server where production data files will reside on your
site for optimal
performance (see <a
 href="file:///home/jim/code2/src/plconfig/docs/man/plconfig.html#--prod-dir"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">--prod-dir</span></a>). <br>
<br>
<span style="font-weight: normal;"></span><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">If not specified, the file host will
default to (localhost).</span></div>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><b><a name="--file-port"></a>--file-port</b><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">=</span><i style="font-weight: normal;">num</i></h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 80px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The
number of the network port (<span style="font-style: italic;">num</span>)
listened to by the Pipeline file management daemon <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plfilemgr</span>(1).&nbsp; <br>
</span></h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 80px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">If
not
specified, the port number will default to (53136).</span></h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><b><a name="--notify-control-port"></a>--notify-control-port</b><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">=</span><i style="font-weight: normal;">num</i></h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 80px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The
number of the network port (<span style="font-style: italic;">num</span>)
listened to by the Pipeline directory change notification daemon <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plnotify</span>(1) for control
requests.&nbsp; <br>
</span></h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 80px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">If
not
specified, the port number will default to (53137).</span></h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 40px;"><b><a name="--notify-monitor-port"></a>--notify-monitor-port</b><span
 style="font-weight: normal;">=</span><i style="font-weight: normal;">num</i></h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 80px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">The
number of the network port (<span style="font-style: italic;">num</span>)
listened to by the Pipeline directory change notification daemon <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plnotify</span>(1) monitoring requests.<br>
</span></h4>
<h4 style="margin-left: 80px;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">If
not
specified, the port number will default to (53138).</span></h4>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 40px;"><b><a
 name="--prod-dir"></a>--prod-dir</b>=<span style="font-style: italic;">dir</span></h4>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 80px;">The absolute path
to the root directory
under which all production data files will reside.&nbsp; In other
words, the location where artists will save their work.&nbsp; This root
production directory should reside on a network accessible
file system such
that all machines which will run Pipeline related programs can access
the directory as (dir). For
optimal performance this directory should reside on the
same host which runs the file management daemon <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">plfilemgr</span>(1) (see <a
 href="file:///home/jim/code2/src/plconfig/docs/man/plconfig.html#--file-host"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">--file-host</span></a>). <br>
</h4>
<h4 style="font-weight: normal; margin-left: 80px;">If not specified,
the production directory will default to (/base/prod).</h4>
<br>
<br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><span style="font-weight: bold;"><a
 name="--class-path"></a>--class-path</span>=<span
 style="font-style: italic;">path<br>
</span>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
An additional set of colon (:) seperated directories (<span
 style="font-style: italic;">path</span>) to search for the JAR files
for the Java
prerequisites described in the <a href="#System_Prerequisites"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">System Prerequisites</span></a><span
 style="font-weight: bold;"></span><span style="font-weight: bold;"> </span>section.&nbsp;
This (<span style="font-style: italic;">path</span>) is appended to the
normal class search path for the <span style="font-weight: bold;">Java
Runtime Environment</span>. Normally this option is not required as the
JAR
files for <span style="font-weight: bold;">JAI</span> and <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Java 3D</span> are usually installed in the
same location as the <span style="font-weight: bold;">JRE</span>.&nbsp;
This option is provided to support non-standard installations of these
support packages.<br>
<br>
</div>
<span style="font-weight: bold;"><a name="--library-path"></a>--library-path</span>=<span
 style="font-style: italic;">path</span><span style="font-weight: bold;"><br>
</span>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
An additional set of (:) seperated directories (<span
 style="font-style: italic;">path</span>) to search for the native
shared object libraries for the Java
prerequisites described in the <a
 href="file:///home/jim/code2/src/plconfig/docs/man/plconfig.html#System_Prerequisites"><span
 style="font-weight: bold;">System Prerequisites</span></a><span
 style="font-weight: bold;"></span><span style="font-weight: bold;"> </span>section.&nbsp;
This path (<span style="font-style: italic;">path</span>) is appended
to the
normal libaray search path for the <span style="font-weight: bold;">Java
Runtime Environment</span>. Normally this option is not required as the
native libraries for <span style="font-weight: bold;">JAI</span> and <span
 style="font-weight: bold;">Java 3D</span> are usually installed in the
same location as the <span style="font-weight: bold;">JRE</span>.&nbsp;
This option is provided to support non-standard installations of these
support packages.<br>
<br>
If not specified, the value of the LD_LIBRARY_PATH environmental
variable is searched instead for native libraries as well as the
standard <span style="font-weight: bold;">JRE</span> locations.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
</div>
<span style="font-weight: bold;"><a name="--lock"></a>--lock</span><br>
<div style="margin-left: 40px;"><br>
Makes the generated configuration files (pipeline.key,
pipeline.profile and pipeline.config) read-only, to protect them from
being overwritten by a later execution of plconfig(1).&nbsp; It is
strongly advised that plconfig(1) be run with this option once a final
configuration has been decided on to prevent accidental damage to your
Pipeline license key and site profile.<br>
</div>
</div>
